➜Bill Gates condemns US government for silencing top scientist, again
http://www.sohu.com/a/427385012_162758	27680
<p><img src="http://p7.itc.cn/q_70/images03/20201026/af644f27a6b242219838ce90c3875eaf.png" width="1000" height="611" /></p>
<p>Bill Gates criticizes U.S. Covid-19 response: Most governments listen to their scientists (CNBC)</p>
<p>Earlier this month, the Microsoft founder and philanthropist Bill Gates lashed out at the Trump administration again for trying to undermine infectious disease expert Dr. Anthony Fauci and other US government scientists during a Politico Playbook virtual discussion, according to CNN.</p>
<p>“We're engaged in something where we're attacking the government's top scientists, not speaking out about how to save lives, but instead undermining the credibility of the person who's the most knowledgeable,” Gates emphasized, "Expertise matters, and the CDC is largely not allowed to speak out. And so, fortunately, Dr. Fauci has risen above the noise level in talking about masks and best practices. And so the fact that they're trying to undermine him, for some reason... That just blows the mind.”</p>
<p>Bill Gates, who has been engaged with works tackling complex global health challenges for years, has long warned of the possibility of a global disease outbreak. “Bill Gates said in an interview with STAT two years ago that he had urged to invest in technologies to respond to a pandemic.” reported by STAT NEWS.</p>            <div class="lookall-box">
<div class="lookall-shadow"></div>
<section class="lookall">
<a href="javascript:;" class="show-all" id="showMore">
<em>展开全文</em>
</a>
</section>
</div>
<div class="hidden-content control-hide">
<p>This is not the first time Gates has voiced the US administration for politicizing science. Dated back to March, Gates warned the US government over calling a quick end to lockdown, fearing that lives would be sacrificed in the bid to resume business-as-usual, and achieve a stock-market rebound, before the virus subsides. “There really is no middle ground, and it’s very tough to say to people, ‘Hey, keep going to restaurants, go buy new houses, and ignore that pile of bodies over in the corner. We want you to keep spending because there’s maybe a politician who thinks GDP growth is all that counts.’” Gates shared his view in a TED interview in the early stage of the pandemic.</p>
<p>Up to now, the US death toll from COVID-19 has risen above 225,000 by this Monday. In a separate interview on Politico in the mid-October, Gates raised again to point out US’ shortcomings in the combat with the coronavirus. “If you’re willing to admit that you’re not doing a perfect job, you could improve this thing very, very quickly,” he said. “Right now, testing, contact tracing -- we're doing among the worst of any country. Just insane.” Without mentioning any names, Gates said that unlike the U.S., many countries have “done very, very well” using the behavioral tools available to help blunt the spread of the coronavirus.</p>
